            <h2><i class="fas fa-book-medical"></i> Understanding Pregnancy Due Dates</h2>
            
            <h3><i class="fas fa-calculator"></i> How Due Dates Are Calculated</h3>
            <p>Pregnancy due dates are typically calculated as 40 weeks (280 days) from the first day of your last menstrual period (LMP). This assumes a 28-day cycle with ovulation on day 14.</p>
            
            <h3><i class="fas fa-list-alt"></i> Different Calculation Methods</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Last Menstrual Period (LMP):</strong> Most common method - 40 weeks from first day of LMP</li>
                <li><strong>Conception Date:</strong> 38 weeks from known conception date</li>
                <li><strong>IVF Transfer:</strong> 38 weeks from 3-day transfer or 37 weeks from 5-day transfer</li>
                <li><strong>Ultrasound:</strong> Based on fetal measurements, most accurate in first trimester</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3><i class="fas fa-baby"></i> Pregnancy Trimesters</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>First Trimester:</strong> Weeks 1-13 - Critical development period</li>
                <li><strong>Second Trimester:</strong> Weeks 14-27 - Often called the "honeymoon period"</li>
                <li><strong>Third Trimester:</strong> Weeks 28-40 - Final preparation for birth</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3><i class="fas fa-exclamation-circle"></i> Important Notes</h3>
            <p>Due dates are estimates - only about 5% of babies are born on their exact due date. Full-term pregnancy is considered 37-42 weeks.</p>
            <p>Always consult with your healthcare provider for personalized medical advice and to confirm your due date through clinical assessment.</p>
        </section>
